question: Could we change technology to restore and then scale humanity’s
capacity to build trusted relationships, which are the bedrock of healthy
societies, economies, and democracies? We identified the possibility for just
such a model in what may seem an unexpected place: the concept at the core of
the social network itself, known as the social graph. The term "social graph"
isn't widely known beyond Internet technolog]]></description><link>https://www.dsnp.org/dsnp-in-relation-to-unfinished/</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Ghost__Post__60c1156d298220000127543e</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Claire Olmstead]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 09 Jun 2021 19:24:52 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Project Liberty began at an event in 2019 on Liberty Island, focused on a question: Could we change technology to restore and then scale humanity’s capacity to build trusted relationships, which are the bedrock of healthy societies, economies, and democracies? We identified the possibility for just such a model in what may seem an unexpected place: the concept at the core of the social network itself, known as the social graph. The term "social graph" isn't widely known beyond Internet technology circles, but it is a digital representation of all the relationships between members of a social network. When we use a social network—as nearly 60 percent of the world does—all the ways we connect, learn, transact, consume, and contribute traverse this essential online circuitry. The social graph holds immense power over us all, and the largest social networks are owned and controlled by powerful, private companies, each built on its own proprietary social graph. The key to change lies in the power of combining our social networks in one unified social graph that is free from corporate control and rewards innovators and value creators directly.</p><p>Late in 2019, <a href="https://www.unfinishedlabs.io/">Unfinished Labs</a> assembled a team and began to build that social graph protocol. The Decentralized Social Network Protocol (DSNP) is the result of their work, and DSNP.org is an independent stewardship organization that serves as the home for ongoing development of the DSNP specifications and open source code.</p><p>Opening the social graph for building is only the beginning. To enable a vibrant ecosystem of apps that leverage the new social graph, Unfinished Labs continues to develop essential tooling for rapid testing and launch of new social apps and integration of social features into existing apps.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Mission & Activities]]></title><description><![CDATA[The mission of DSNP.org is to support community development of open source
technology and protocols to create a single, universally accessible, and
decentralized social graph.

Our primary activity is stable and responsible stewardship of the Decentralized
Social Network Protocol (DSNP). Because the protocol is available for anyone to
use, for both commercial and non-commercial purposes, our role is to help
implementors ensure the integrity and decentralized governance of the unified
and univers]]></description><link>https://www.dsnp.org/mission-activities/</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Ghost__Post__60c115482982200001275433</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Claire Olmstead]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 09 Jun 2021 19:24:16 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>The mission of DSNP.org is to support community development of open source technology and protocols to create a single, universally accessible, and decentralized social graph.</p><p>Our primary activity is stable and responsible stewardship of the Decentralized Social Network Protocol (DSNP). Because the protocol is available for anyone to use, for both commercial and non-commercial purposes, our role is to help implementors ensure the integrity and decentralized governance of the unified and universally accessible social graph. The integrity of the graph includes DSNP's promises about people's privacy and control over their communications.  To serve these goals:</p><ul><li>We provide a framework for DSNP-related working groups and ongoing standards development (based loosely on the role of the IETF in Internet governance), and help participants interface with other standards bodies when needed.</li><li>We keep watch for unanticipated or adversarial centralization, and coordinate community response as needed. Decentralized systems usually have centralizing forces circulating within them, for example nodes that grow especially large and influential, and preserving true decentralization can sometimes require coordinated action.</li><li>We arrange virtual and in-person gatherings of DSNP implementors, both to help accelerate development and usage of DSNP as a technology and to ensure that there is a community of mutually familiar implementors who share a vision of DSNP's purpose.</li><li>We coordinate legal defense of DSNP if necessary (e.g., community patent defense).</li><li>We work transparently and in public as much as possible.  Anyone should be able to see what what DSNP.org is doing without necessarily being a participant.</li></ul><p>Control of content flowing over DSNP is not within the scope of DSNP.org's mission, and we do not take part in development of content filtering policy; that is for nodes in and gateways to the graph to decide and implement.  Our goal is maintenance of the protocol and the decentralized social graph in such a way that the public interest is well-served by having individuals use DSNP-based technologies to communicate.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Guiding Principles]]></title><description><![CDATA[We ground our work in a fairly simple ethos.  We've tried to lay them out here.
 This articulation might change over time, but our animating principles should
remain consistent.

 * Never build anything alone
 * Flexible beats prescient
 * Open wins from the bottom up

Our ethos echo the Bedrock Principles of the wider Unfinished ecosystem.  We
look forward to the Unfinished team rolling out those bedrocks into public view.
 For now, we'll just note that we align with their grounding in connecti]]></description><link>https://www.dsnp.org/guiding-principles/</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Ghost__Post__60c11523298220000127542b</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Claire Olmstead]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 09 Jun 2021 19:23:33 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>We ground our work in a fairly simple ethos.  We've tried to lay them out here.  This articulation might change over time, but our animating principles should remain consistent.</p><ul><li>Never build anything alone</li><li>Flexible beats prescient</li><li>Open wins from the bottom up</li></ul><p>Our ethos echo the Bedrock Principles of the wider Unfinished ecosystem.  We look forward to the Unfinished team rolling out those bedrocks into public view.  For now, we'll just note that we align with their grounding in connection, vision, and collaboration.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Governance]]></title><description><![CDATA[DSNP.org is governed by a Board of Directors, with the assistance of an Advisory
Council. To provide a stable base for early growth, the initial Board has a
majority representation from our founding partner, Unfinished, while also
including a significant number of independent directors. As the DSNP ecosystem
expands and matures, we will also be updating the process for selecting Board
members accordingly, with the expectation that Unfinished will become just one
constituent among many, so that t]]></description><link>https://www.dsnp.org/governance/</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Ghost__Post__60c114f32982200001275420</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Claire Olmstead]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 09 Jun 2021 19:23:01 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>DSNP.org is governed by a Board of Directors, with the assistance of an Advisory Council. To provide a stable base for early growth, the initial Board has a majority representation from our founding partner, Unfinished, while also including a significant number of independent directors. As the DSNP ecosystem expands and matures, we will also be updating the process for selecting Board members accordingly, with the expectation that Unfinished will become just one constituent among many, so that the Board represents the composition of the entire DSNP ecosystem, as befits community-governed public infrastructure.</p><h2 id="why-an-entity">Why an entity?</h2><p>DSNP.org is an independent entity to ensure that the community of people and organizations that depend on the protocol have a place to convene, discuss matters of common concern, and take collective action where appropriate.  One such matter is the technical development of the protocol itself, of course: establishing the standards that make DSNP-enabled applications mutually compatible, and updating those standards to meet the community's functionality needs in ways that align with DSNP's mission and values.  Another example is addressing regulatory concerns, including helping regulators understand what DSNP is and what it does.  These kinds of activities are best coordinated by an independent entity that is able to foster discussion among a diverse group of stakeholders without being beholden to any single stakeholder. DSNP.org also needs to be able to adjust its governance to preserve this role in a changing environment, which means it should not be subject to the governance constraints of any other organization.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Who We Are]]></title><link>https://www.dsnp.org/who-we-are/</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Ghost__Post__60c114c52982200001275416</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Claire Olmstead]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 09 Jun 2021 19:22:04 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded/></item><item><title><![CDATA[Karl Fogel]]></title><description><![CDATA[Karl Fogel [https://duckduckgo.com/?q=karl+fogel] has been an open source
